Metastatic sigmoid cancer, KRAS wild type, BRAS wild type with liver metastasis.

[end section id="20102"]

[start section id="20103"]

Per Dr Strange's note dated 7-29-2010:
Mrs. Tolbert is a very pleasant 66-year-old patient who has been referred to Medical Oncology by Dr. Cook to obtain an opinion regarding the future management of her metastatic colon cancer.
The patient underwent a routine colonoscopy on March 11, 2010, and was found to have a mass in the sigmoid.  Biopsies confirmed the presence of an adenocarcinoma.  The same-day a CT-scan of the abdomen and pelvis was performed which revealed multiple intrahepatic metastases.  The CEA was 145.  Subsequently the patient was started on systemic chemotherapy with modified FOLFOX-6 plus bevacizumab.  After four cycles a CT-scan revealed an excellent response with almost complete resolution of the intrahepatic lesions and good response of the primary tumor to chemotherapy.
The patient consulted Nanticoke Valley Memorial Hospital in June of 2010.  At that time our recommendation as to hold bevacizumab, continue chemotherapy with modified cycles of FOLFOX and then bring the patient back with a CT-scan of abdomen, pelvis and PET CT-scan for surgical evaluation.
Mrs. Tolbert now returns to Nanticoke Valley Memorial Hospital after she has stopped Avastin about eight weeks ago and has received one more cycle of FOLFOX.  She has been tolerating the treatment very well, although the last treatment cycle which was her seventh cycle of oxaliplatin resulted in more prolonged sensorineural toxicity, in particular cold sensitivity.  Otherwise she is doing fine, she is motivated to move forward with the surgical approach. She is currently on low-molecular-weight heparin and has stopped her Coumadin about a week ago.

[end section id="20103"]

